<div class="page-hero">
  <div class="page-hero-inner">
    <div class="eyebrow">The toolkit</div>
    <h1>How to advocate for your cat <em>at the vet</em></h1>
    <p>You are not just a bystander in your cat's care. You are the person who sees them every day, knows their baseline, notices the subtle changes. This toolkit gives you the language and the questions to make that knowledge count.</p>
  </div>
</div>

<section class="advocate-section">
  <div class="advocate-inner">

    <div class="toolkit-block" id="questions">
      <h2>Questions to Ask at Every Appointment</h2>
      <p>These are the questions that change outcomes — the ones too many owners don't know to ask. Print this. Bring it to the appointment.</p>

      <div class="question-group">
        <h3>About the diagnosis</h3>
        <ul class="question-list">
          <li>What is the specific diagnosis, and how confident are you?</li>
          <li>What other conditions could explain these symptoms?</li>
          <li>What tests would rule those out?</li>
          <li>Is there a specialist I should see?</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="question-group">
        <h3>About the numbers</h3>
        <ul class="question-list">
          <li>What does this specific number mean for my cat's quality of life?</li>
          <li>What's the trend compared to last time?</li>
          <li>What is our target range, and why?</li>
          <li>Are we optimising for longevity, quality of life, or both?</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="question-group">
        <h3>About treatment</h3>
        <ul class="question-list">
          <li>What are we treating, what are we not treating, and why?</li>
          <li>What are the side effects of this medication?</li>
          <li>What happens if we don't treat this?</li>
          <li>Are there alternative approaches we haven't tried?</li>
          <li>What would you do if this were your cat?</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="question-group">
        <h3>About prognosis</h3>
        <ul class="question-list">
          <li>What's the realistic best-case here?</li>
          <li>What would make you most concerned?</li>
          <li>What signs should bring us back immediately?</li>
          <li>At what point do we reconsider the current approach?</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="toolkit-block" id="pushback">
      <h2>When to Push Back (and How)</h2>
      <p>"There's nothing more we can do" is sometimes accurate. It is also sometimes the end of a vet's thinking rather than the end of the options. These situations warrant a second look:</p>

      <div class="pushback-list">
        <div class="pushback-item">
          <div class="pushback-trigger">Your cat has stopped eating and anti-nausea medication hasn't been discussed</div>
          <div class="pushback-ask">Ask: "Have we considered uraemic nausea? Would anti-nausea medication like Cerenia be appropriate?"</div>
        </div>
        <div class="pushback-item">
          <div class="pushback-trigger">You're being told to switch to a prescription diet but your cat refuses it</div>
          <div class="pushback-ask">Say: "My cat will not eat the kidney diet. What is the priority — getting food in, or the specific diet? Can we manage phosphorus another way?"</div>
        </div>
        <div class="pushback-item">
          <div class="pushback-trigger">The recommendation is based on a single test result</div>
          <div class="pushback-ask">Ask: "Should we retest before making a treatment change? What's the variance on this test?"</div>
        </div>
        <div class="pushback-item">
          <div class="pushback-trigger">You're told there's nothing more to do</div>
          <div class="pushback-ask">Ask: "Is there a specialist — an internal medicine vet or a veterinary neurologist — who might have additional options?"</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="toolkit-block" id="labs">
      <h2>Reading Lab Results Yourself</h2>
      <p>You don't need a vet degree to understand the basics of what's in the bloodwork. Understanding the numbers means you can ask better questions — and spot concerning trends before they're flagged.</p>
      <p>See the detailed lab guide in the <a href="{{ '/conditions/ckd/#lab-results' | url }}">CKD section</a> for specific markers. General principles:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Trends matter more than single readings.</strong> One elevated creatinine can be a lab error, dehydration, or a bad day. A rising trend across three tests is meaningful.</li>
        <li><strong>Ask for the actual numbers,</strong> not just "normal" or "elevated." You can't track a trend without specific values.</li>
        <li><strong>Request copies of every blood panel.</strong> Keep them. You'll want to see patterns over time.</li>
        <li><strong>Context changes everything.</strong> Was your cat dehydrated? Had they eaten recently? Stress can affect results.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

  </div>
</section>
